Java Tokens :-
=============
Tokens are the smallest units of a Java program.
They are the individual parts of Java code.

There are 4 types of tokens in Java:

Keywords

Identifiers

Separators

Literals

1ï¸âƒ£ Keywords

Keywords are predefined reserved words in Java.

Java is a case-sensitive language.

Keywords must always be written in lowercase.

Java contains 50 keywords.

âœ… Examples:

int
class
public
static
void
if
else
return
2ï¸âƒ£ Identifiers

Identifiers are the names given to Java components.

Examples of components:

Class names

Variable names

Method names

Identifier Rules

Identifiers can contain alphabets (Aâ€“Z, aâ€“z) and digits (0â€“9).

Identifiers must not start with a digit.

Keywords cannot be used as identifiers.

Special symbols are not allowed except:

_ (underscore)

$ (dollar)

âœ… Valid Identifiers:

studentName
_empId
$salary
marks1

âŒ Invalid Identifiers:

1name      // Cannot start with number
int        // Keyword not allowed
total-marks // Special symbol not allowed
Naming Convention (CamelCase Rules)
ğŸ“Œ Class Name

Must start with an uppercase letter.

If multiple words are used, the first letter of each word should be uppercase.

âœ… Examples:

Student
EmployeeDetails
BankAccount
ğŸ“Œ Variable / Method Name

Must start with a lowercase letter.

If multiple words are used:

First word starts with lowercase.

Each new word starts with uppercase.

âœ… Examples:

studentName
calculateTotalMarks()
bankAccountNumber
3ï¸âƒ£ Separators

Separators are used to separate blocks and statements in Java.

Common Separators:
Separator	Purpose
{ }	Define blocks
;	End a statement
( )	Method parameters
[ ]	Arrays
,	Separate multiple variables

Example:

class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello");
    }
}
4ï¸âƒ£ Literals

Literals are the actual values assigned in Java code.

There are 4 types of literals:

Number

Integer

Float

Character

String

Boolean

1ï¸âƒ£ Number Literals

Numbers can be written directly.

System.out.println(10);    // Integer
System.out.println(10.5);  // Float
2ï¸âƒ£ Character Literals

Must be enclosed in single quotes ' '

Only one character is allowed.

âœ… Examples:

System.out.println('H');
System.out.println('&');
System.out.println('1');

âŒ Invalid:

System.out.println('10');  // Compile Time Error (CTE)
3ï¸âƒ£ String Literals

Must be enclosed in double quotes " "

No length limitation

âœ… Examples:

System.out.println("sheela420");
System.out.println("3245326540");
System.out.println("true");
System.out.println("");
4ï¸âƒ£ Boolean Literals

Boolean values are predefined:

true

false

âœ… Examples:

System.out.println(true);
System.out.println(false);
âœ… Summary
Token Type	Description
Keywords	Predefined reserved words
Identifiers	Names given to program elements
Separators	Symbols used to separate code structure
Literals	Fixed values used in code
